frameDefinitions: The lexical units in this frame have to do with an Entity being in a State of order or disorder.

These words describe the recovery or healing of a Patient from an Affliction without reference to the influence of any Treatment or Healer (see the Cure frame).  '' 'My injuries had not yet completely healed.'
This frame concerns Acts and State_of_
A generally large group of people, the Combatants, are engaged in a chaotic, violent, and usually protracted Fight amongst themselves.
An Entity persists in a stable situation called a State
frameExamples: Soon the system was in total <t><fex name='St'>chaos</fex></t>.
My injuries had not yet completely <t>healed</t>.
A lot of people suspect that blocking savers' access to their money <t>violates</t> the new constitution's explicit ban on compulsory loans to the government.
listRoleDefinitions: The object or phenomenon which exists in the <fen>State</fen> of disorder.  It is common for the <fen>Entity</fen> to be null instantiated in this frame.
The <fen>State</fen> in which the <fen>Entity</fen> exists.  Usually the <fen>State</fen> will be the target-denoting noun.
The time at which the <fen>Entity</fen> exists in the <fen>State</fen>.
The location where the <fen>Entity</fen> exists in the <fen>State</fen>.
The    Patient may either be expressed as the External Argument or, as in Health.Cure, may occur as the possessor of the Affliction (an example of role conflation):
This role is the injury, pain or disease experienced by the Patient.  Affliction occurs either as an External Argument of verbs or as a PP Complement of nouns or verbs:
Where Body Part is expressed as a separate constituent (rather than in phrases such as <ment>the wound on Pat's arm</ment>), it occurs as an External Argument:
The time at which the recovery takes place.
The location where the recovery takes place.
The <fen>Protagonist</fen>'s behavior is in or out of compliance with norms.
This role identifies the <fen>Act</fen> that is judged to be in or out of compliance with the <fen>Norm</fen>s.
A <fen>State_of_affairs</fen> may violate a law or rule.
This role identifies the rules or <fen>Norm</fen>s that ought to guide a person's behavior.
This role identifies the <fen>Time</fen>  when the act of compliance or non-compliance occurs.
The <fen>Combatants</fen> participate as fighters in the <fen>Fight</fen>.
The violent activity.
When the <fen>Fight</fen> takes place.
Where the <fen>Fight</fen> takes place.
Concrete or abstract entity
State of an Entity.
listRoleExamples: Subsequent bomb alerts caused <fex>travel</fex>chaos in the London Underground.
More <fex>chaos</fex> awaits the Soviet Union unless it ditches perestroika for a Thatcherite purge of its economy.
Monica Lewinksy in 1998 gave him a rich new target, as did the electoral chaos <fex>of 2000</fex>.
Lying in bed listening to the chaos <fex>downstairs</fex>, he knew his conquest had only been temporary.
Jo's <fex><t>violation</t></fex> of the no trespassing law came as a surprise.
John violated <fex>the law</fex> by not paying taxes.
The football referee's controversial call led to a bloody free-for-all <fex>among the fans</fex>.
I couldn't help but watch as several bruised people reentered the <fex><t>melee</t></fex>.
